<br>
Milambus and Nyca seem to say that you forfiet all rot turns that occur during any multiday rot (unless you want to give up your multiday rot). I can understand the logic used to decide upon this, but think that perhaps Karadins idea (or my perception of it) is a little more understandable. No other rot is sacrificed because a guild is up for 2 rots in 1 day.<br>
<br>
The reason I really feel like this is, what determines that (lets use NB) NB leaves VT for another kill? The fact that they accomplish the kill? Or the fact that no one from NB is left in VT? What if NB was due for Sev on day 2 of their VT turn...they just happen to have 8 people that were late to VT and therefore couldnt attend (I dont know their rules, this is for the sake of argument). Those 8 from NB go and kill Sev, but no one left VT, is this wrong? What if they needed a cleric, and ONE cleric left to help with Sev? If any of these are acceptable, what actually determines &quot;holding&quot; of VT, or &quot;leaving&quot; VT for that matter?<br>
<br>
Im not trying to be argumentative, but this is a VERY liekly scenario with a few rot mobs now killable with very small forces and some guilds having enough players to do multiple high level raids at the same time.<br>
